    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Right to Die With Dignity</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from medical student Jennifer Heaton on Pain Relief Promotion Act passed by House says right to die of terminal illness with dignity and control should be a personal decision (Sept 19 article)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Ban on Assisted Suicide'' (editorial, Sept. 19):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Ban on Assisted Suicide'' (editorial, Sept. 19):</p>
        <p>The Pain Relief Promotion Act, passed by the House and soon to be voted on in the Senate, is yet another example of federal legislation of morality and the regulation of health care provision by outsiders.</p>
        <p>Policy can be swallowed more easily when it results in many overall goods to society, as in the cases of seat-belt or smoking laws. But the individual decisions regarding end-of-life care have negligible effects on the welfare of the population.</p>
        <p>The right to die of a terminal illness with dignity and control should be a personal decision. To deny someone this choice unnecessarily takes away that liberty we so value as Americans.</p>
        <p>JENNIFER HEATON  Berkeley, Calif., Sept. 19, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is a medical and public health student at Washington University and the University of California at Berkeley.</p>
      </block>
